Let e=(u,v) and f be edges of a network. A head move of e to f consists of the following steps (Figure <ref>):


  * delete  e;

  * subdivide f with a new node v';

  * suppress the indegree-1 outdegree-1 node v;

  * add the edge (u,v').

Subdividing an edge (u,v) consists of deleting it and adding a node x and edges (u,x) and (x,v). Suppressing an indegree-1, outdegree-1 node x with parent u and child v consists of removing  edges (u,x) and (x,v) and node x, and then adding an edge (u,v).

Head moves are only allowed if the resulting digraph is still a network (Definition <ref>). 
We say that a head move is a distance-d head move if, after step 2, a shortest path from v to v' in the underlying undirected graph has length at most d+1 (number of edges in the path).

